        pdfAllocMethodology: 'INVESTMENT GUIDANCE METHODOLOGY: Your risk profile was determined by a questionnaire scoring system. Two components were calculated: (1) Time Horizon Score (0-5 points) based on years until retirement, and (2) Risk Tolerance Score (5-20 points) based on your responses to five questions about investment comfort, market reaction, goals, experience, and withdrawal timeline. The combined score was compared against the plan\'s risk profile thresholds to determine your profile (Conservative through Aggressive). Fund recommendations are based on matching your risk profile to appropriate model portfolios, target date funds, and allocation funds available in the plan. Fund performance data is sourced from Fi360, Yahoo Finance, and Morningstar and is updated quarterly. Trailing returns shown are historical and assume reinvestment of dividends and capital gains. The expected return ranges are based on approximately 90 years of U.S. market history for portfolios with similar stock/bond allocations.',

        pdfContribMethodology: 'CONTRIBUTION CALCULATOR METHODOLOGY: Paycheck deductions are calculated as follows: Pretax contributions are a percentage of gross (pre-tax) pay. Roth contributions are a percentage of net (after-tax) pay. Employer match is calculated as 25 cents per dollar contributed (25% match rate), applied to total contributions up to a maximum of 10% of gross pay. If total contributions are below 10%, the full match is not received. Estimated net pay is calculated by subtracting Roth contributions from net pay; pretax contributions do not directly reduce net pay since they are deducted before taxes. When only net pay is provided, gross pay is estimated using an approximate deduction rate of 28% (representing federal income tax, state income tax, FICA, and benefits). The contribution comparison table maintains the participant\'s current pretax/Roth ratio when projecting different contribution levels.',

        pdfGrowthMethodology: 'PROJECTED GROWTH CALCULATOR METHODOLOGY: Future balance projections use biweekly compounding over 26 pay periods per year. The formula applied each period is: Balance = Previous Balance x (1 + Annual Return / 26) + Contribution + Employer Match. Pretax contributions are calculated as a percentage of gross pay; Roth contributions are calculated as a percentage of net pay. Employer match is added to the pretax balance. Pretax and Roth balances are tracked separately throughout the projection. The annual rate of return is applied uniformly and does not account for market volatility, sequence-of-returns risk, or varying returns across asset classes. Projections do not account for contribution limits ($23,500 for 2025, plus $7,500 catch-up for age 50+), salary increases, inflation, investment fees beyond fund expense ratios, or early withdrawal penalties.',

        pdfLongevityMethodology: '401(k) LONGEVITY CALCULATOR METHODOLOGY: The calculator uses a month-by-month simulation to determine how long savings will last. Each month: (1) Investment return is calculated as Balance x (Annual Return / 12). (2) Taxes are applied only to the pretax portion of returns at the combined federal and state marginal tax rates; Roth returns grow tax-free. The Roth ratio is carried forward from the Growth Projector. (3) The monthly withdrawal is deducted from the balance. (4) At the end of each 12-month period, the withdrawal amount increases by the inflation rate to maintain purchasing power. The simulation runs until the balance reaches $0 or 100 years (1,200 months). The "Desired Years" feature uses a binary search algorithm to find the maximum sustainable starting withdrawal that lasts the specified number of years. The 80% income target comparison subtracts Social Security and pension income from 80% of gross salary to determine the minimum 401(k) withdrawal needed. Social Security is excluded if retirement age is before 62.',

